To respond to this tweet, registrations have been closed because no miner surpasses a stage of incentive, meaning that even if you have a new miner, you couldn't achieve a satisfactory incentive. Even if registrations were open, no miner would surpass the stage to avoid being deregistered, and therefore they would lose money. This is due to the fact that the current miners respond perfectly to requests, and they have the advantage of being older on the network. The subnetwork will be opened next week, however, with an update that should rebalance the incentive curve and prevent this from happening. I would like to mention that I do not mine on my subnet in any way, and I do not receive any rewards related to mining on my subnet.

messages.content: My decision is simply based on discussions with miners due to the losses they were facing, as my subnet is one that requires the most GPU resources.

Moreover, subnets close their registration during major updates (such as switching to a different protocol), where it is necessary to pause registrations in order not to unbalance the network and give miners time to update their equipment. They also close when bugs are discovered or vulnerabilities are found, which is very useful to limit damage. By the way, you are talking about subnet 25, but if you took an interest in their work, you would see that they are redesigning the architecture of their subnet for better stability. It is not a network with an easy architecture.

Subnet registrations will be opened at 14:30 (UTC+2), and will be closed as soon as the update is ready (will be ready this week branch **ver/1.0.0**, with production starting on Monday).
I'm just warning you, if your miners don't manage to reach a good level of incentive, it's not at all abnormal (you have to wait for some miners to break down to hope for a spot).
